    "solution": "Sulfur (S) is the central atom in SO3. Sulfur has 6 valence electrons. Oxygen (O) has 6 valence electrons. In SO3, sulfur forms double bonds with each of the three oxygen atoms. \nWe can use the steric number to determine hybridization. Steric number = (number of sigma bonds) + (number of lone pairs). \nIn SO3, Sulfur forms 3 sigma bonds (one sigma bond with each oxygen) and has 0 lone pairs. Thus, the steric number is 3 + 0 = 3. \nA steric number of 3 corresponds to sp2 hybridization. The molecule is trigonal planar, with bond angles of 120 degrees. Although resonance structures can be drawn with one S-O single bond and two S=O double bonds (or vice-versa), the actual structure is an average of these, and the sulfur atom is sp2 hybridized.",
